				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Adapt or Exit with style.<a name="62915"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 19 04 1:03 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Myscha, first off I want to apologize for using your post to base what I want to say.  I just needed to get some things off of my chest, and many statements here sparked my thoughts, so I replied.  I just wasn't sure where else to post.  That being said, I agree with you that many posts have that &quot;Soe nerfed me personally so I'm leaving!!&quot; feel to it, but there are a few points I have to disagree with.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">On one hand I shake my head, thinking &quot;I think that person was just looking for an excuse, they must be really burned out. They should take a step away.&quot;
<br />

<br />
On another hand I shake my head thinking &quot;Yep bandwagon jumper.. cry FOUL and make threats and maybe they will fix the game feature.</span></blockquote>
<br />
Some of us fall into a different category.  Okay, maybe it's just me, but the reason why my drum has been gathering dust is because I'm just plain tired of it all.  
<br />
- I'm tired of needing to be in a top end guild just to get flagged for content, let alone better equipment. 
<br />
- I'm tired of being required to be online at a certain time just to be able to join a raid for a shot at further content.  
<br />
- I'm tired of the endless xp/aaxp grind.  Sure, I have no problem getting groups or soloing to get the necessary xp.  But that's just it, I'm pursuing xp not as a result of exploration and/or fun, but just so I can meet guild requirements just so I can be with friends.
<br />
- I'm tired of the fact that gear and flags and xp (and songs) is what gets you into groups and guilds, and not pure talent and a likable personality.  
<br />
- I'm tired of the fact that all of these flags, xp, and gear is required to join your friends in a guild.  Guilds are generally not looking at folks based on skill and personality.  But even if they did, one cannot join said friends without flags at the very least.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">-I have never once seen a Bard AOE kite in my life. I loved chanting and grouping. I hate raiding its boring. </span></blockquote>
<br />
I have not ae'd for xp at all in my 65/170ish career.  I have solo'd about 2/3 of that xp.  That is not to say that I haven't used it for other means though such as ts item farming or factioning.  Given a few more aa to up the mods on my instruments, I was looking forward to having ae kiting as another option for xp besides swarming gargs/hobs in pon, or chanting elsewhere.  Now that is not possible.  To me, the truth of the matter is not the fact that ae kiting needed to be fixed, but the fact that it was removed from the game.  A skill that has been around since the very beginning.  SoE could have just reduced the affect, not remove it entirely.  What would happen if SoE took quad kiting from druids and wizards?  It is one of their class defined abilities but they both would still have other options to be able to solo.  Think they would accept it?
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">-Yes lots of aspects of this class have changed. </span></blockquote>
<br />
I have been playing since just before Kunark came out.  Once Luclin was released, I rolled my bard which has since then been my main character.  I have seen many things change.  One of the reasons why I love the bard so much is the fact that I have been able to adapt to each and every change.  Even though change is good, and I welcome it, I do not welcome change in the wrong directions or for the wrong reasons.  Imho, since SoE took over, changes to EQ has been about the almighty dollar and not about the player base.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">-If you have been a hardcore EQ player for eons and you want to &quot;hang up your drum&quot; sure get it off your chest. </span></blockquote>
<br />
Harmonea was a very respected person on these forums.  I'm not sure if she considers herself hardcore, but she was definitely a strong voice in this community.  To see her go is definitely a sign of the times.  She is not the only one that has had too much and decided to finally quit.  I may not be hardcore by anyones definition, but I was incredibly dedicated to the class, and have always tried to post positive replies on these forums and those over at tCH.  But I am a nobody, which is why I didn't make a post about my retirement. 
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Go try some other MMP games. some have nice features and they all have much better graphics. They are not as complete as EQ quite simply because of the 5 years that EQ was able to mature and got constant development beyond a &quot;token live team&quot; like most MMP games end up with. </span></blockquote>
<br />
I'm going to see how Saga of Ryzom plays out, and have signed up for the Wish Beta 2.0 coming out in December.  Wish is touting itself to be the anti-eq, with a seamless world (yes, done before) and a dedicated online team of DM's who continuously introduce new content.  When mobs die, they die for good.  When quests are completed, they are completely finished.  The world will evolve based on players actions, and not what sells the most expansion cd's.  But this is just based on what I have read.  I hope to see how all of this works sometime around 2Q 2005.
<br />

<br />
As I said, I'm tired of it all, and now I'm tired of rambling, so I leave you all with a fond farewell.  I may however post still on occasion.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
